#Topic ##
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#Topic Filter Quality

Filter Quality trades speed for image filtering when the image is scaled.
A lower Filter Quality draws faster, but has less fidelity.
A higher FIlter Quality draws slower, but looks better.
If the image is unscaled, the Filter Quality choice will not result in a noticable
difference.

#Import Enum SkFilterQuality # map to look at followed by key in map?

Filter Quality is used in the paint passed as a parameter to
#List
  SkCanvas::drawBitmap
  SkCanvas::drawBitmapRect
  SkCanvas::drawImage
  SkCanvas::drawImageRect
  #ToDo probably more... ##
#List ##
and when the Paint has a Shader specialization that uses an Image or a Bitmap.

Filter Quality is kNone_SkFilterQuality by default.

#Example
#ToDo  how to specify the mandrill image ##
void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
    SkPaint paint;
    canvas->scale(.2f, .2f);
    for (SkFilterQuality q : { kNone_SkFilterQuality, kLow_SkFilterQuality, 
                               kMedium_SkFilterQuality, kHigh_SkFilterQuality } ) {
        paint.setFilterQuality(q);
        canvas->drawImage(image.get(), 0, 0, &paint);
        canvas->translate(550, 0);
        if (kLow_SkFilterQuality == q) canvas->translate(-1100, 550);
    }
}
#Example ##

    /**
     *  Return the filter level. This affects the quality (and performance) of
     *  drawing scaled images.
     */
#Method SkFilterQuality getFilterQuality() const

getFilterQuality returns the Filter Quality set in the paint. A lower setting
draws faster; a higher setting looks better when the image is scaled.

#Example
    SkPaint paint;
    SkDebugf("kNone_SkFilterQuality %c= paint.getFilterQuality()\n",
            kNone_SkFilterQuality == paint.getFilterQuality() ? '=' : '!');

    #StdOut
        kNone_SkFilterQuality == paint.getFilterQuality()
    #StdOut ##
#Example ##

#Method ##


#Method void setFilterQuality(SkFilterQuality quality)

setFilterQuality sets the Filter Quality in the paint. A lower setting
draws faster; a higher setting looks better when the image is scaled.

quality is not checked to see if it is valid.

#Example
    SkPaint paint;
    paint.setFilterQuality(kHigh_SkFilterQuality);
    SkDebugf("kHigh_SkFilterQuality %c= paint.getFilterQuality()\n",
            kHigh_SkFilterQuality == paint.getFilterQuality() ? '=' : '!');

    #StdOut
        kHigh_SkFilterQuality == paint.getFilterQuality()
    #StdOut ##
#Example ##

#SeeAlso SkFilterQuality, Image Scaling

#Method ##

#Topic ##
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#Topic Paint Color 

#Subtopic
    Color Alpha
    Color RGB
#Subtopic ##

Paint Color specifies the Red, Blue, Green, and Alpha values used to draw a filled
or stroked shape in a
32-bit value. Each component occupies 8-bits, ranging from zero: no contribution;
to 255: full intensity. All values in any combination are valid.

Paint Color is not premultiplied;
Color Alpha sets the transparency independent of Color RGB: Red, Blue, and Green.

The bit positions of Color Alpha and Color RGB are independent of the bit positions
on the output device, which may have more or fewer bits, and may have a different arrangement.

#Table
# bit positions # 31 - 24 # 23 - 16 # 15 - 8 # 7 - 0 ##
#               # Alpha   # Red     # Blue   # Green ##
#Table ##

#Example
    void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
        SkPaint paint;
        canvas->clear(SK_ColorWHITE);  // opaque white
        paint.setColor(0x8000FF00);  // transparent green
        canvas->drawCircle(50, 50, 40, paint);
        paint.setARGB(128, 255, 0, 0); // transparent red
        canvas->drawCircle(80, 50, 40, paint);
        paint.setColor(SK_ColorBLUE);
        paint.setAlpha(0x80);
        canvas->drawCircle(65, 65, 40, paint);
    }
#Example ##

#Method SkColor getColor() const

    Retrieve the Alpha and RGB color from the paint packed into 32 bits.
    Use helpers SkColorGetA, SkColorGetR, SkColorGetG, and SkColorGetB to extract
    the color component.

    #Example
        SkPaint paint;
        paint.setColor(SK_ColorYELLOW);
        SkColor y = paint.getColor();
        SkDebugf("Yellow is %d%% red, %d%% green, and %d%% blue.\n", (int) (SkColorGetR(y) / 2.55f),
                (int) (SkColorGetG(y) / 2.55f), (int) (SkColorGetB(y) / 2.55f));

        #StdOut
            Yellow is 100% red, 100% green, and 0% blue.
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

    #SeeAlso SkColor

#Method ##

#Method void setColor(SkColor color)

    Set Color Alpha and Color RGB used when stroking and filling. The color is a 32-bit value
    packing 8 bit components for Alpha, Red, Blue, and Green. 

    #Param color    The packed unpremultiplied ARGB color. ##
        
    #Example
        SkPaint green1, green2;
        unsigned a = 255;
        unsigned r = 0;
        unsigned g = 255;
        unsigned b = 0;
        green1.setColor(a << 24 + r << 16 + g << 8 + b << 0);
        green2.setColor(0xFF00FF00);
        SkDebugf("green1 == green2);

        #StdOut
            Yellow is 100% red, 100% green, and 0% blue.
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

    #SeeAlso SkColor setARGB, SkColorSetARGB

#Method ##

#Method uint8_t getAlpha() const

    Retrieve Color Alpha from the Paint Color used when stroking and filling.

    #Return Color Alpha ranging from zero, fully transparent, to 255, fully opaque. ##

    #Example
        SkPaint paint;
        SkDebugf("255 %c= paint.getAlpha()\n", 255 == paint.getAlpha() ? '=' : '!');

        #StdOut
            255 == paint.getAlpha()
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

#Method ##

#Method void setAlpha(U8CPU a)

    setAlpha replaces Color Alpha, leaving Color RGB 
    unchanged. An out of range value triggers an assert in the debug
    build.

    #Param a    Color Alpha component (0..255) of Paint Color. ##

    #Example
        SkPaint paint;
        paint.setColor(0x00112233);
        paint.setAlpha(0x44);
        SkDebugf("0x44112233 %c= paint.getAlpha()\n", 0x44112233 == paint.getAlpha() ? '=' : '!');

        #StdOut
            0x44112233 == paint.getAlpha()
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

#Method ##

#Method void setARGB(U8CPU a, U8CPU r, U8CPU g, U8CPU b)

    Set Paint Color used when drawing solid fills. The color components range from 0 to 255.
    The color is unpremultiplied;
    Color Alpha sets the transparency independent of Color RGB.

    #Param a    The amount of alpha, from fully transparent (0) to fully opaque (255). ##
    #Param r    The amount of red, from no red (0) to full red (255). ##
    #Param g    The amount of green, from no green (0) to full green (255). ##
    #Param b    The amount of blue, from no blue (0) to full blue (255). ##
        
    #Example
        SkPaint transRed1, transRed2;
        transRed1.setARGB(255 / 2, 255, 0, 0);
        transRed2.setColor(SkColorSetARGB(255 / 2, 255, 0, 0));
        SkDebugf("transRed1 %c= transRed2", transRed1 == transRed2 ? '=' : '!');

        #StdOut
            transRed1 == transRed2
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

    #SeeAlso setColor, SkColorSetARGB

#Method ##

#Topic Paint Color ##

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#Topic Paint Style

#Subtopic
    Style Fill
    Style Stroke
        Stroke Width
            Hairline
        Stroke Cap
            Zero Length Segments
        Stroke Join
            Miter Construction
            Miter Limit
            Bevel Construction
    Style Stroke and Fill
#Subtopic ##

Paint Style specifies if the geometry is filled, stroked, or both filled and stroked.
Some shapes ignore Paint Style and are always drawn filled or stroked.

Set Paint Style to kFill_Style to fill the shape.
The fill covers the area inside the geometry for most shapes.

Set Paint Style to kStroke_Style to stroke the shape.
The stroke covers the area described by following the shape's edge with a pen or brush of
Stroke Width. The area covered where the shape starts and stops is described by Stroke Cap.
The area covered where the shape turns a corner is described by Stroke Join.
The stroke is centered on the shape; it extends equally on either side of the shape's edge.

Set Paint Style to kStrokeAndFill_style to draw both simultaneously. The stroke and fill
share all paint attributes; for instance, they are drawn with the same color.

#Enum Style

#Code
    enum Style {
        kFill_Style,
        kStroke_Style,
        kStrokeAndFill_Style,
    };
    enum {
        kStyleCount = kStrokeAndFill_Style + 1
    };
#Code ##

kFill_Style applies to Rectangle, Region, Rounded Rectangle, Circle, Oval, Path, and Text. 
Bitmap, Image, Patch, Region, Sprite, and Vertex are painted as if kFill_Style is set,
and ignore the set Paint Style.
The Path Fill Type specifies additional rules to fill the area outside the path edge,
and to create an unfilled hole inside the shape.
Paint Style is set to kFill_Style by default.

kStroke_Style applies to Rectangle, Region, Rounded Rectangle, Arc, Circle, Oval,
Path, and Text. 
Arc, Line, Point, and Points are always drawn as if kStroke_Style is set,
and ignore the set Paint Style.
The stroke construction is unaffected by the Path Fill Type.

kStrokeAndFill_Style applies to Rectangle, Region, Rounded Rectangle, Circle, Oval, Path, and Text.
Path is treated as if it is set to SkPath::kWinding_FillType,
and the set Path Fill Type is ignored. 

Use stroke and fill to avoid hitting the same pixels twice with a stroke draw and
a fill draw.

Path with SkPath::kEvenOdd_FillType drawn with
kStroke_Style and then drawn with kFill_Style may draw differently from one drawn
with kStrokeAndFill_Style.

kStyleCount is used to verify that Paint Style is a legal value.

#Enum ##

#Method Style getStyle() const

    Returns Paint Style; whether the geometry is filled, stroked, or filled and stroked.

    #Example
        SkPaint paint;
        SkDebugf("Style::kFillStyle %c= paint.getStyle()\n",
                Style::kFillStyle == paint.getStyle() ? '=' : '!');

        #StdOut
            Style::kFillStyle == paint.getStyle()
        #StdOut ##
    #Example ##

#Method ##

#Method void setStyle(Style style)

    Set Paint Style; used whether the geometry is filled, stroked, or filled and stroked.
    setStyle has no effect if style is not a legal Style value.

    #Example
        void draw(SkCanvas* canvas) {
            SkPaint paint;
            paint.setStrokeWidth(5);
            SkRegion region;
            region.op(140, 10, 160, 30, SkRegion::kUnion_Op);
            region.op(170, 40, 190, 60, SkRegion::kUnion_Op);
            SkBitmap bitmap;
            bitmap.setInfo(SkImageInfo::MakeA8(50, 50), 50);
            uint8_t pixels[50][50];
            for (int x = 0; x < 50; ++x) {
                for (int y = 0; y < 50; ++y) {
                    pixels[y][x] = (x + y) % 5 ? 0xFF : 0x00;
                }
            }
            bitmap.setPixels(pixels);
            for (auto style : { SkPaint::kFill_Style,
                                SkPaint::kStroke_Style,
                                SkPaint::kStrokeAndFill_Style }) {
                paint.setStyle(style);
                canvas->drawLine(10, 10, 60, 60, paint);
                canvas->drawRectCoords(80, 10, 130, 60, paint);
                canvas->drawRegion(region, paint);
                canvas->drawBitmap(bitmap, 200, 10, &paint);
                canvas->translate(0, 80);
            }
        }
    #Example ##

#Method ##

#SeeAlso Canvas Shape, Path Fill Type, Path Effect, Style Fill, Style Stroke
#Topic Paint Style ##

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#Topic Style Fill

